								<h1><strong>Anwitaman Datta</strong></h1>
							</header>
							<p align="justify">I joined NTU Singapore in 2006, where I hold the position of an Associate Professor at the <font color="#008080">College of Computing and Data Science</font>. <br>
                                                                           I did my undergraduate studies at <font color="#008080">IIT Kanpur, India</font> and 
                                                                           my doctoral dissertation at <font color="#008080">EPFL, Switzerland</font>. During 
                                                                           2014-2018 I was a co-founder and non-executive director of <font color="#008080">Qiv Storage Pte Ltd</font>, where we developed and translated intellectual property for <a href="https://patents.google.com/patent/US8928503B2/en">self-repairing (locally repairable) erasure codes</a> to create highly fault-tolerant and performant multi-disk storage appliances. Between 2019-2023, I served as a Senior Scientific 
                                                                         Officer in a consulting role with Irish fintech start-up <font color="#008080">QPQ.IO</font>, working with a geographically distributed team spearheading research and development of <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2208.07665">1DLT</a>,  disentangling the EVM (Ethereum Virtual Machine) from the underlying consensus mechanism (where third party consensus services could be used in a plug-and-play manner), providing a means to deploy EVMs on demand in a light weight, fast and yet secure manner. Between 2024-2025, (on leave from NTU) I worked at the Cyber Technology Institute, School of Computer Science and Informatics at <font color="#008080">DMU, Leicester, UK</font> as a Professor of Cyber Security (where I currently continue to hold a honorary Professorship). Contemporaneously, I did a secondment with <font color="#008080">DMU London</font> to aid bootstrap its MSc in Responsible Data Analytics program.<br>
						</div>
